#!/bin/sh
# Example NUT SHUTDOWNCMD: shut down an ESXi host, using govc (the vSphere
# CLI already installed in this image).
#
# This deliberately issues a single forced host shutdown rather than
# looping over VMs first: this container may itself be running on a VM on
# that host, so a script that shuts down other VMs before the host can be
# killed mid-run before it ever reaches the host.shutdown call. `-f` shuts
# the host down even with VMs still running -- see `govc host.shutdown -h`
# ("-f  Force shutdown when host is not in maintenance mode").
#
# For that forced shutdown to gracefully stop guest OSes (instead of
# hard-powering them off) rather than looping VMs manually here, configure
# the "Stop Action" per VM once on the host itself: Host > Configure >
# Virtual Machines > VM Startup/Shutdown (autostart), where each VM can be
# set to "Guest Shutdown" (requires VMware Tools) with a delay. See:
# https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vsphere/vsphere/8-0/vsphere-virtual-machine-administration/managing-virtual-machinesvsphere-vm-admin/edit-vm-startup-and-shutdown-settingsvsphere-vm-admin.html
#
# Caveat: that autostart policy is disabled on hosts in an HA-enabled
# cluster, so on such a cluster this forced shutdown will hard-power-off
# VMs instead of gracefully stopping their guest OS.
#
# Setup:
#   1. Create a dedicated ESXi user with just enough privilege to shut down
#      the host (Host.Config.Shutdown), rather than reusing root.
#   2. Copy this file to shutdown-esxi.sh (kept out of git via
#      .gitignore), fill in real values below, then in .env set:
#      SHUTDOWN_CMD="/scripts/shutdown-esxi.sh"
set -eu

export GOVC_URL="https://esxi.example.local"
export GOVC_USERNAME="shutdown-svc"
export GOVC_PASSWORD="change-me"
export GOVC_INSECURE=1

govc host.shutdown -f
